photo.title: Ownership inscriptions of Odoardo Gualando (d. 1587?), Francesco Venturi (1576-1614), Nicolaus Bargiacchus, and Sir Sydney Carlyle Cockerell (1867-1962)
photo.description: Adouardi Gualandi Pisani [Early ms. ownership inscription, struck through, of Odoardo Gualando. Born in Pisa, he was elected Bishop of Cesena in 1557, where he served until 1587 -- his date of death? EDIT 16 (and CERL, following them) give both 1587 and 1597 as his terminal dates. His VIAF entry is agnostic. The Catholic Hierarchy website claims that he resigned in 1588, with a note that the year is uncertain; they are probably calculating from the appointment of his successor, Camillo Gualandi, in the spring of 1588. DNB heading: Gualandus, Adovardus] Francisci Venturij [...] Francisci Venturij [Two early ms. ownership inscriptions in different hands, the latter repeated at the foot of the following leaf. One or the other (if the first is not a transcription of the second) might perhaps be identified with Francesco Venturi (1576-1614) of Florence, lawyer, linguist, and canon. Established form: Venturi, Francesco, 1576-1614] Nicolaj Bargiacchj [Early (18th-century?) ms. ownership inscription of Nicolaus Bargiacchus. A man of this name is mentioned in the "Epistola ad P.F. Fogginium" of Angiol Maria Ricci (d. 1776), professor of Greek in Florence, as "Nicolaus Bargiacchius I.U.D. tum multa eruditione, tum MSS. bibliotheca sua notus, & [Antonio Maria] Salvinio familiaritate coniunctissimus" (in Dissertationes Homericae habitae in Florentino Lyceo, v. 1 (Florence: Albizinii, 1740), p. 329.] SC Cockerell Richmond Surrey 1902 [Autograph of Sir Sydney Carlyle Cockerell (1867-1962), English book collector and museum curator. A personal friend of William Morris (and his executor at the Kelmscott Press) and John Ruskin, he is best known as curator of the Fitzwilliam Museum at the University of Cambridge from 1908-1937. He possessed an extensive collection of medieval and Renaissance manuscripts. (His son Christopher invented the hovercraft.) A note in Cockerell's hand on the inside front cover of this volume indicates that he bought it at Sotheby's on 14 November 1902. Established form: Cockerell, Sydney Carlyle, Sir, 1867-1962] Penn Libraries call number: Inc M-342 All images from this book

photo.title: Ownership inscription of the Biblioteca Altempsiana
photo.description: Ex bibli[othe]ca. Altemps[ia]na. [Ms. ownership inscription of the Biblioteca Altempsiana. It was founded by the Austrian churchman Markus Sittikus von Hohenems, Cardinal Altemps (1531-1595), nephew of Pope Pius IV, at the Palazzo Altemps in Rome and expanded by his nephew Mark Sittich, Archbishop of Salzburg (1574-1619). (Both men are also known by the Italianized form of their name, Marco Sittico Altemps, Altemps being a calque of Hohenems.) The library was eventually absorbed into the Biblioteca vaticana.] Established heading: Biblioteca altempsiana. Penn Libraries call number: IC5 Al821 543r 1555 Folio All images from this book

photo.title: Ownership inscription of Gottlieb Paul Christ (1707-1786)
photo.description: Theophili Pauli Christii, Coburgensis. MDCCXXXVIII Liber perrarus. [Gottlieb Paul Christ (1707-1786), professor, librarian and court functionary at Ansbach. In their finding aid Aldine Press Books at the Harry Ransom Humanities Research Center, The University of Texas at Austin (Austin: The Center, 1998), Craig W. Kallendorf and Maria X. Wells identify the ex-libris "Theophili Pauli Christi" as "Gottlieb Paul Christ (18th cent.), prof. at Anspach Gymnasium". According to his biographical entry in C.A. Baader, Lexikon Verstorbener Schrifsteller des 18. und 19. Jahrhunderts (Augsburg: Von Jenisch- und Stage'schen Buchhandlung, 1825), Bd. 2, T. 1, p. 22, Christ was born in Coburg but came to Ansbach in 1728 to take service with Freiherr von Seckendorff (probably Christoph Ludwig Freiherr von Seckendorff-Aberdar). He went abroad on several diplomatic missions and became the librarian for the Ansbacher Schlossbibliothek. (According to E.F.C. Oertel in Georg Ludwig Oeder der erste Rektor bei der Einweihung des neuen Gymnasiums in Ansbach am 12. Juni 1737 ... (Ansbach: Oertel, 1837) p. 54-55, he got the job in 1738; according to the Schlossbibliothek's history web page, he was the second librarian to be appointed.) In 1737 he was appointed professor at the gymnasium in Ansbach and published a number of works on historical subjects; he also continued to serve at court as a councillor. DNB heading: Christ, Gottlieb Paul 1707-1786] Other examples of Gottlieb Paul Christ provenance Penn Libraries call number: IC P5876 504o Folio All images from this book

photo.title: Ownership inscription of Con­stan­tine Huy­gens (1596–1687)
photo.description: 16 Constanter 50 [Ownership inscription of Con­stan­tine Huy­gens (1596–1687). Constantijn Huygens, was a Dutch Golden Age poet and composer. He was secretary to two Princes of Orange: Frederick Henry and William II, and the father of the scientist Christiaan Huygens. Books from his library typically have his "Constanter" ownership inscription on the title page. Information about his library and the efforts to identify books owned by Huygens can be found at the Constanter website. Additional information about Huygens's library can be found at Notabilia, Princeton University's rare book provenance blog. Established heading: Huygens, Constantijn, 1596-1687 Penn Libraries call number: IC D2352.9 1596 Folio Catalog record All images from this book

photo.title: Scatological woodcut illustration to accompany a poem praising Johannes Nas's work by a fellow Catholic author known only as Bibobacherius. Used by Wolfgang Eder of Ingolstadt
photo.description: Scatological woodcut illustration to accompany a poem praising Johannes Nas's work by a fellow Catholic author known only as Bibobacherius. Used by Wolfgang Eder of Ingolstadt. Birgit Wiedl notes that the Eselritt (ass-ride), like the Sauritt (sow-ride), "is the typical feature of a type of pamphlet that is known as Schandbild or Schmähbrief ('defamatory picture/letter') that ... show the person(s) they are directed against as riding backwards; if groups of people are depicted, they might also engage in the 'typical' habit of occupying themselves with the animal's behind, shoving seals or money pouches into its hindquarters, or devouring its excrement" ("Laughing at the Beast" in Laughter in the Middle Ages and Early Modern Times, ed. A. Classen (Berlin: De Gruyter, 2010), p. 351). Donkeys are commonly depicted eating thistles; in the 16th century, this image also becomes emblematic of miserliness or the failure to appreciate the good things in one's possession: cf. emblem 86 in Andrea Alciati's Emblemata. (The anagram "Nasus/As(i)nus," which appears in some anti-Nas polemic, may also have influenced the choice of mount.) The dog, pig and flies pursuing the donkey's droppings require no further comment. The rider is tonsured and dressed as a friar (note the spurs, however) and bears a shield which identifies him as Johannes Nas. The upper portion of the shield shows a pair of scissors, three needles (probably) and a thimble (possibly). Johannes Nas began life as a tailor and included a pair of shears on his episcopal arms; they are common in satirical depictions of him: cf. this image and this image. In these images the tailor's tools are accompanied by a goat, negatively associated with lasciviousness and stubbornness (cf. Wiedl, p. 353, and the entry "Goat" in H.B. Werness, The Continuum Encyclopedia of Animal Symbolism in Art (New York: Continuum, 2006)). Here, however, the shears, needles and thimble are paired with an elephant's head; Werness notes that the elephant was used to symbolize dullness in the 16th century (entry "Elephant"). Established heading: Eder, Wolfgang, fl. 1578-1596 Penn Libraries call number: GC55 N1700 583a All images from this book
